They say good developers are lazy. A tedious process is no match for a lazy developer. Below is an experiment in laziness. It&rsquo;s a proof of concept for using Web Components without having to manually import each one.
I&rsquo;m not sure exactly what to call it. It grazes the definitions of lazyloading, autoloading, and dependency injection, so I went with the laziest term.
Let&rsquo;s set the scene, and find out if it&rsquo;s a worthwhile developer convenience, or ease-of-use gone mad&hellip;

&ldquo;Finally,&rdquo; I thought, &ldquo;an excuse to play with WebGL at work!&rdquo;
This year, I had the good fortune of contributing to a keynote presentation at Red Hat Summit. During the keynote, an audience of 5,000 played a mobile web game created by our team. The game was backed by several microservices which we modified on stage while the audience played.
My contribution was to display, in a visual and engaging way, the live network traffic flowing through our system.
